<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n08040j"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08040j">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08040j"> 40(j)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> how much do you / want to lose</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Le fait suivant s&apos;est pass&eacute; sous mes yeux, dans une banque. Un jeune homme demandait qu&apos;on lui achet&acirc;t des titres, d&apos;une esp&egrave;ce tr&egrave;s sp&eacute;culative, &agrave; terme. Il h&eacute;sitait &agrave; fixer le chiffre de l&apos;op&eacute;ration qu&apos;il allait tenter, et questionnait &agrave; ce sujet l&apos;employ&eacute; de la banque. Celui-ci brave homme jugeant que son interlocuteur &eacute;tait un novice imprudent, lui r&eacute;pliqua:&mdash; <mark>Combien voulez-vous perdre?</mark> <font color="green">[The following took place under my own eyes, in a bank. A young man expressed the wish to buy shares of a very speculative nature: futures. He hesitated to decide on the amount he was going to chance and asked the advice of the bank clerk. The latter, thinking that his client was an imprudent novice, replied: &lsquo;How much do you want to lose?&rsquo;]</font> <small> J Cr&eacute;pieux-Jamin, <a name="JCJL" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#JCJL"><cite title="source">Les &eacute;l&eacute;ments de l'&eacute;criture des canailles</cite></a> (1923) 301-2</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
